DAB300 - LAB 3 - Building an Image Classifier from Scratch ¶

The main goal of this lab is to create an image classifier from scratch using the Keras package. You will create a binary classifier based on an object type of your choice. The classifier will accept images and then predict whether or not a given image contains that object. For example, if you chose your object to be a cat, then the classifier would accept images and predict 1 if it believes there is a cat in the image or a 0 if not.

Part 1: Prep Work - Choose an Object & Create a Dataset¶

Create a Dataset¶

  • Chosen Object : mapple leave
  • 80 pictures of mapple leaves with various of forms, colors
  • 80 pictures of other objects excluding mapple leaves
  • Training set includes 50 picture of mapple leaves, and 50 pictures of other objects. These are directories of train set 
      + ../mapledataset/train/maple/
  + ../mapledataset/train/nomaple/
  • Validation set includes 15 picture of mapple leaves, and 15 pictures of other objects. These are directories of test set 
      + ../mapledataset/test/maple/
  + ../mapledataset/test/nomaple/
  • Test set includes 15 picture of mapple leaves, and 15 pictures of other objects. These are directories of validation set 
      + ../mapledataset/val/maple/
  + ../mapledataset/val/nomaple/

def fn_BuildModel(p_optimizer,p_loss,p_metrics):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), input_shape=input_shape))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    
    model.add(Conv2D(32, (3, 3)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))

    model.add(Flatten())
    model.add(Dense(16))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    
    model.add(Dense(1))
    model.add(Activation('sigmoid'))

    model.compile(optimizer=p_optimizer,
                loss=p_loss,
                metrics=[p_metrics])
        
    return model


def fn_Train(modelname, model, p_train_gen, p_epochs, p_batch_size, p_val_gen, p_test_gen):
    print('Modelname:',modelname)
    print('Optimizer:', p_optimizer)
    print('Loss',p_loss)
    print('Metrics',p_metrics)    
    
    early_stop = EarlyStopping(monitor = 'val_accuracy', patience = 3)
    
    start_time = time.time()
    
    print('Model Compile with optimizer, loss function and evaluation method')
    
    print('Model Training to see the tensor shapes and number of parameters for each layer')
    # The values for the training loss and accuracy, as well as the validation loss and accuracy, are stored in the history variable
    history = model.fit_generator(p_train_gen,
                    epochs = p_epochs, 
                    validation_data=p_val_gen,
                    validation_steps = p_batch_size,verbose=2) 
       
    print('Total Training Time (second):', time.time() - start_time)
    
    print('Visualize the progress our network makes on the loss and accuracy as the number of epochs increases.')

    history.history.keys()
    history_dict = history.history # the dictionary that has the information on loss and accuracy per epoch

    loss_values = history_dict['loss']   # training loss
    val_loss_values = history_dict['val_loss'] # validation loss

    epochs = range(1, len(loss_values)+1)  #creates list of integers to match the number of epochs of training

    # code to plot the results
    plt.plot(epochs, loss_values, 'b', label="Training Loss")
    plt.plot(epochs, val_loss_values, 'r', label="Validation Loss")
    plt.title("Training and Validation Loss")
    plt.xlabel("Epochs")
    plt.xticks(epochs)
    plt.ylabel("Loss")
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

    # As above, but this time we want to visualize the training and validation accuracy
    acc_values = history_dict['accuracy']
    val_acc_values = history_dict['val_accuracy']

    plt.plot(epochs, acc_values, 'b', label="Training Accuracy")
    plt.plot(epochs, val_acc_values, 'r', label="Validation Accuracy")
    plt.title("Training and Validation Accuracy")
    plt.xlabel("Epochs")
    plt.xticks(epochs)
    plt.ylabel("Accuracy")
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()
    

    print('Prediction using test set.')    
    test_loss, test_acc = model.evaluate(p_test_gen, verbose=2)
    print(test_acc)
    return
    
   
p_loss = 'binary_crossentropy' 
p_metrics = 'accuracy'
p_epochs=20
p_batch_size=3
p_optimizer= 'rmsprop' #rmsprop
model = fn_BuildModel(p_optimizer,p_loss,p_metrics)
model.summary()   
fn_Train('Sequential Model',model,train_gen, p_epochs, p_batch_size, val_gen, test_gen)

Conclusion :¶

  • After tuning many model, above model is the best. The optimizer "rmsprop" is used, and the loss function is "binary_crossentropy". Model is trained with batch_size = 3.
  • The accuracy of validation can reach 0.96 at the 10th epoch. And, the accuracy of train is higher than the accuracy of validation. The trend is fluctuated and has quite linear direction. However, it is not completely a good model. The loss of validation set tends to increase and always higher than the loss of train set, and the gap becomes higher when the number of epochs increases. This phenonmenon can be considered that the model may be overfitting

Part 3: Using Data Augmentation¶

Dataset Verification¶

You should verify that the training, validation, and test sets have the correct number of images (the os functions should help with this) and that the data is organized in a folder structure that will work with your image data generators.

Dataset Loading and Processing with Create Image Data Generators¶

You should now create image data generators for your training, validation, and test datasets that will allow you to feed them into your model in batches. The images should be resized to 148x148 pixels and scaled so all pixel values are between 0 and 1.

Add Data Augmentation¶

You should now add data augmentation to your training data generator. All available types of augmentation should be used.

Print an image and examples of the same image augmented in different ways. (The .load_img() and .flow() methods may be helpful here.)

Create and Evaluate a Baseline Model¶

Use the best model from Part 2 to train with the augmented data and evaluate on the validation data to get a baseline accuracy for the new model trained on the augmented dataset.

Tune the Model¶

With a more complex training set, you may be able to improve the accuracy through adjustments to the baseline model architecture and tuning the hyperparameters.

Report Accuracy on Test Set¶

Your final step is to make predictions using the test set and report the final test set accuracy. It may be helpful to use batch_size=1 for this step.

print('Tuning Model')


def fn_Build_OptimizedModel(p_optimizer,p_loss,p_metrics):
    model = Sequential()
    model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3), input_shape=input_shape))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Conv2D(64, (3, 3)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2), strides=(2,2)))
    Dropout(0.2)
    
    model.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Conv2D(128, (3, 3)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    Dropout(0.2)
    
    model.add(Conv2D(256, (3, 3)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Conv2D(256, (3, 3)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    Dropout(0.2)

    model.add(Conv2D(512, (3, 3)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Conv2D(512, (3, 3)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Conv2D(512, (3, 3)))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2, 2)))
    Dropout(0.2)
    
    model.add(Flatten())
    model.add(Dense(4096))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    model.add(Dense(4096))
    model.add(Activation('relu'))
    Dropout(0.2)
    
    model.add(Dense(1))
    model.add(Activation('sigmoid'))

    model.compile(optimizer=p_optimizer,
                loss=p_loss,
                metrics=[p_metrics])
        
    return model

Regarding to Part 3 :¶

  • Adding data augmentation methods is applied such as: rotation, horizontal and vertical flipping, zooming, brightness adjust. However, the models are not better, and overfitting issue has not resolved.

  • The new model that is built with optimization purpose. However, the model is not better. It's even the worse model because the model cannot learn. The accuracty for train fluctuated from 0.4 to 0.7, but the accuracy of validation phases were not changed.

In general, the current adding augmentation data and tuning model do not gain expected result. There are some conclusion that can be draw as below:

  • The changing shape / color / bright/ or rotation of image can not resolve the overfitting issue of the model because the dataset is too complex to learn. Moreover, current implementing was not able to load and save augmented images as expectation. So the number of images in the training set doesn't increase, this lead to not help for training phases and overfitting resolving.

  • The optimzed model is added more layers and "Dropout" layer as well to reduce overfitting. However. it doesn't work. Therefore, with current dataset which is small and complex, tuning model by adding layers and dropout layer could not help.

Due to having no more time, we decided to pause the practice here. However, adding augmentation data to increase the trainset is the step we will investigate more to improve the model.
